explanation:
To determine whether OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext violates the MISRA rule forbidding memcmp to compare null-terminated strings you must examine not only the body of this function but also any code it expands/calls or invokes indirectly via callbacks.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: listed as a callee in the static call graph. Inspect its implementation to see whether it calls memcmp (directly or indirectly) or performs string comparisons using memcmp.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET (macro / inline accessor): The iterator uses this macro to obtain 'record'. The macro expansion could call other helpers or perform comparisons (including memcmp); you must inspect its definition.
- OS_object_iter_t (definition): You need the exact struct layout to know the types of fields (token, base, limit, match, arg). This determines what data is being compared and whether any string pointers are involved.
- token type used by iter->token (e.g. OS_object_token_t) — fields obj_idx, obj_id: The token fields (obj_idx, obj_id and possibly name/string fields) reveal whether the iterator is operating on string identifiers and whether any comparisons could involve null-terminated strings.
- OS_common_record_t (definition): The record obtained from the object table may contain fields (names, IDs) that could be compared as strings; inspect its fields to see if memcmp would be used on null-terminated strings.
- iter->match function-pointer type / prototype and any implementations (callbacks passed to iterator): The iterator calls iter->match if present. That callback is provided elsewhere; it may use memcmp to compare strings. You must inspect the callback type and all implementations that can be passed to this iterator to determine if memcmp is used for null-terminated strings.
- OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED (macro / constant): Knowing the value and type of this macro helps confirm whether obj_id is an integer ID or potentially a string handle — relevant to decide whether any comparisons are string comparisons.
- memcmp (standard library function): To find all uses across the codebase (including within the above symbols), you must inspect memcmp usages to see if any uses compare null-terminated strings (the MISRA violation target).

Inspecting these symbols (and the implementations of any callbacks passed into iter->match) will allow a reviewer to determine if memcmp is being used to compare null-terminated strings either directly in OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext, in macros it expands, in callees, or in user-supplied match callbacks.
